{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "buddhism-expert",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "TN needed — this is not wordplay, it's the argument",
    "content": "**This is not etymological wordplay — it is the structural backbone of the author's entire reinterpretation of metaphysics.** The loss is serious and requires a TN. But do NOT use \"above-the-phenomenal\" in running text.\n\n**1. Yes, losing it is a significant problem.** The author's central move in Essay 4 is reinterpreting 形 in 形而上 as 现象 (phenomena) rather than the traditional reading of \"visible form.\" This reinterpretation is what Q7 in the Memo was about — the Kantian expert flagged it as \"a significant hermeneutical move.\" If the English reader cannot see that \"the metaphysical\" literally means \"above the phenomenal,\" they miss that the author is not just USING metaphysics but REDEFINING what the word itself means. The sentence \"道 is 形而上 and 礼 is 形\" only works as an argument because 形而上 contains 形 — the reader needs to see that 形而上 is built on top of 形, just as metaphysical constructions are built on top of phenomena.\n\n**2. A TN is the right solution.** This is exactly the kind of case TNs exist for — structural information in the source language that cannot be rendered in the target language. The TN should appear at the first occurrence of 形而上 in Essay 4 and explain:\n\n\"The Chinese term 形而上 (xing er shang) literally means 'above form/phenomena (形, xing).' The author reads 形 here as 现象 (phenomena), making 形而上 mean 'that which is constructed above phenomena.' This etymology is active throughout the essay: when the author contrasts 形而上 (the metaphysical) with 形 (the phenomenal), the reader should hear 'above-phenomena' contrasted with 'phenomena itself.'\"\n\n**3. Do NOT use \"above-the-phenomenal\" in running text.** It is too heavy, too hyphenated, and would need to appear dozens of times across Essays 4-7. \"The metaphysical\" works fine as the running translation — the TN teaches the reader to hear the etymology inside it. After reading the TN, the sentence \"the Way is the metaphysical, while ritual conduct is the phenomenal\" becomes transparent: the Way is above-phenomena, ritual conduct IS phenomena."
  }
}
